aws::graph::propositions: # FK Lightplanes FK9 Accident Near Canton, Georgia
FK Lightplanes FK9 is a light-sport airplane.
N611SP is a FK Lightplanes FK9 airplane.
N611SP was registered to a private individual.
N611SP was operated by a private individual.
The accident occurred on January 4, 2014.
The accident occurred at approximately 1530 eastern standard time.
N611SP was substantially damaged following a partial loss of engine power.
The partial loss of engine power occurred while in cruise flight.
The accident occurred near Canton, Georgia.
The pilot made an off airport forced landing to an open field.
The certificated private pilot was not injured.
The passenger was not injured.
Visual meteorological conditions prevailed during the flight.
No flight plan was filed for the flight.
The flight was destined for Cobb County Airport – McCollum Field.
Cobb County Airport – McCollum Field is identified by the code RYY.
Cobb County Airport – McCollum Field is located in Kennesaw, Georgia.
The flight originated from Mustang Field Airport.
Mustang Field Airport is identified by the code 0GA1.
Mustang Field Airport is located in Hartwell, Georgia.
The flight departed at approximately 1500.
The flight was operated under the provisions of Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91.
The flight was classified as a personal flight.
During cruise flight, the fuel pressure gauge indicated a decrease in fuel pressure.
The fuel pressure decreased from 5.4 gallons per hour to 0.1 gallons per hour.
The engine RPM decreased after the fuel pressure dropped.
The pilot activated the auxiliary fuel pump.
The pilot was able to restart the engine after activating the auxiliary fuel pump.
Only partial power was restored to the engine.
The airplane was unable to maintain altitude.
The pilot performed an off airport emergency landing to a nearby field.
Upon landing, the airplane encountered a berm.
The airplane became airborne after hitting the berm.
The airplane landed hard after becoming airborne.
The left main landing gear separated from the airplane during the hard landing.
The nose landing gear separated from the airplane during the hard landing.
The landing gear collapse was the defining event of the accident.

text:
# Factual Information

## History of Flight

Enroute-cruise | Loss of engine power (partial)
--- | ---
Landing | Off-field or emergency landing
Landing-landing roll | Landing gear collapse (Defining event)

On January 4, 2014, about 1530 eastern standard time, a FK Lightplanes FK9, light-sport airplane, N611SP, was substantially damaged following a partial loss of engine power while in cruise flight near Canton, Georgia. The pilot subsequently made an off airport forced landing to an open field. The certificated private pilot and passenger were not injured. Visual meteorological conditions prevailed and no flight plan was filed for the flight destined for Cobb County Airport – McCollum Field (RYY), Kennesaw, Georgia. The fight originated from Mustang Field Airport (0GA1), Hartwell, Georgia, about 1500. The airplane was registered to and operated by a private individual under the provisions of Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 as a personal flight.

According to the pilot, while in cruise flight the fuel pressure gauge indicated a decrease in fuel pressure from 5.4 gallons per hour (gph) to 0.1 gph and the rpm subsequently decreased. After activating the auxiliary fuel pump, he was able to restart the engine; however, only partial power was restored. Unable to maintain altitude, an off airport emergency landing was performed to a nearby field. Upon landing the airplane encountered a berm, became airborne, and landed hard, which resulted in the left main landing gear and nose landing gear to separating from the airplane.
